The combined value of equity is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Combined Equity}&=\$3,246+\$6,311\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$9,557}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the combined value of equity of the two existing firms is $9,557.

The combined value of debt is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Combined Debt}&=\$12,954+\$19,889\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$32,843}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the combined value of debt of the two existing firms is $32,843.

Then, the value of debt of the new firm is solved below: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Debt}&=\text{Asset's Value}-\text{Equity}\\[15pt]
&=\$42,400-\$7,579\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$34,821}
\end{aligned}$$

The computed value of equity is deducted from the asset's value to determine the value of debt. 

Thus, the value of the debt of the new firm is $34,821.

The gain or loss on equity is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Change in Equity}&=\$7,579-\$9,557\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{(\$1,978)}
\end{aligned}$$

The combined equity is deducted from the equity of the new firm to determine the gain or loss of shareholders. 

Therefore, the loss of shareholders is ($1,978).

The gain or loss on debt is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Change in Debt}&=\$34,821-\$32,843\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,978}
\end{aligned}$$

The combined debt is deducted from the equity of the new firm to determine the gain or loss of bondholders. 

Therefore, the gain for bondholders is $1,978.
